Event 5 was the quarantine 4D event. This was when I was first in line. We were all required to put 3D glasses on and the walls and props were painted with glow paint. The combination of the paint and the glasses created a very disorienting atmosphere. I saw a woman laughing in the corner and turned around the greet someone who had been trying to sneak up on me. At one point, we walked across a rope bridge. Then towards the end we walked across another bridge through a rotating cylinder, which threw me off balance for a second. At the end, we were asked to dispose of our glasses.

The first 'scary' environment was the bus right at the beginning of the first section. After entering Eastern State and filling in consent forms, just past the section where they ask if you want blood painted on your face, you are held for a moment and then allowed through. At this point, you board a bus, dimly lit, with several people sitting in seats throughout. There is a near-constant strobe, so it is difficult to make out objects, but I kept waiting for someone to jump out from behind a seat the whole way through - this did not happen. Upon reflection, this was most likely just to build anticipation, but it was super scary regardless.

This was one of the most uncomfortable sections, because guards were seeking to jump scare anyone they could, and it was consistently very dark or strobe-lit, so motion and objects were inconsistent and hard to pick out.

In the very last section, there were a couple of ballon-typed tunnels that touched us. You could tell they were just full of air, but they were the only things through the whole event with which we interacted physically, which made that experience the worst of any. I think the biggest problem was the inevitability of it touching me. I didn't want to touch anything, but you couldn't get away from it.

When I was leading in the second section, we were supposed to be ducking under/around some lasers in the big hallway, and being yelled at if we did not do so. At one point, I was staring down the hall to try and make out some consistent movement to focus on as I was walking. In the midst of the strobe lights, there were suddenly several black-clad people just wafting past me getting very close. It was pretty scary, because they appeared and disappeared in a matter of moments.

There was one particular actor/moment that I found disturbing. In the hallway entering the infirmary, there was a person standing next to a gurney with this animatronic character that was retching and screaming. The actor was trying to comfort or quiet it, and the thing just kept writing and screaming the whole time we walked past. It didn't help that I was walking last through this part. It was pretty scary.

The scariest part was this room that had hanging bodies in it. The scary part wasn't the hanging bodies exactly, but there was also a strobe light in the room so you couldn't see where you were going. The strobe was moving so fast that it looked black at times, so you kept accidentally walking into the hanging bodies/whatever the hell these things were that were maybe human or silicone hanging from the ceiling. For the icing on the cake, people were also emerging from the ground to scare you from below, so it was a double whammy. Who knows! There were probably some sounds in there too but I just remember actually touching the bodies on accident and being grossed out.

I think one of the other memorable things is the lady in the beginning. She is essentially the introduction lady who lays down the rules and tells you not to curse, touch the actors, etc. She was dressed in a nurse's outfit with blood on it, and kept saying that we were never going to return from the haunted house. Also, she had an accomplice that came from some hole in the wall that talked to the audience too. She asked people were they were from and if they had ever been to the haunted house before, etc.

One of them, covered in bloody gauze, approached me. At first they were behind me, then were by my side and then, crawling on the ground below me near my left foot.

There was a guard character standing near a computer screen in a mock control room. The theme of the room was the alarms going off because the infection had begun. The computer was broken, the screen was just blue with an error message and the actor was out of character, kinda laughing with us about how it was not working.

I accidentally made eye contact with a clown performer. There were at least four of them in the room, I remember seeing one in each corner and being surprised because usually the actors were more spread out but here they seemed like they were everywhere. She had high pig tails and scary make-up but I didn't look at her face, I looked down at her long polka dot dress and stockings. She asked me if I liked clowns and called me a "terrible liar" when I said yes.

A male person with scary white contacts was behind bars, shaking at them and reaching out to try and touch people. Chains rattled around him and when he reached out at me, I recoiled against the wall and said "please don't touch me!" and surprised myself because I didn't think his intentions were to touch me, just to scare me into thinking he would. He later moved out from behind the cage, showing that it was just an act and he could in fact "escape" at any time.

In the dark hall with the smoke and lasers there were a lot of dark hooded figures walking around not being especially scary. You couldn't see their faces and they all seemed very tall to me. They milled about and didn't approach anyone. I don't know how effective they were at being scary in the context of the haunted house but they were different compared to all the other actors- most of whom had select phrases and tricks.

There was a patient strapped to a metal bed and someone in a bloody smock/doctor's apron talking about sacrificing our body parts. He said "give us your ears!" In a later part of the same room, someone was asking for teeth. I remember thinking ears was too silly and not scary enough, while the idea of harvesting teeth and the decor of a demented dentist's office had me creeped out.

There was an actor strapped to a human slingshot kinda apparatus. They were standing on a platform and would jump down, then the stretchy rubber bands attached to the persons arms pulled them back to the spot. The actor was in a straight jacket, I think with a mask covering the lower part of their face. There was another actor nearby, I guess just to be a spotter or maybe help with the timing or with the instrument. It was the only acrobatic performance. I thought it could have been scarier but I did remember thinking it seemed like fun to fling yourself towards scared people.

In the blacklight room there was someone I caught moving back into their original position to hide and scare people. They were in an all black suit with colorful polka dots and hid against the corner. They were camouflaged. Since the timing was off, they didn't try to scare me and waited for the next group of victims. After seeing where that actor was hiding, I started to check the corners for potential scares.
